<TITLE> DMCH starts DNA testing process </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 4 (bdnews24.com)Relatives of those still missing since the BDR mutiny thronged Dhaka Medical College Hospital forensic department on Wednesday, to assist efforts to confirm the identities of remaining bodies through DNA testing. The forensic department began collecting blood, hair and other samples from close relatives of the missing for possible DNA matches with three out of five bodies remaining at DMCH morgue. 2 'primarily identified' Tuesday Two bodies were 'primarily identified' by relatives on Tuesday, one an officer on the army's latest missing list. Authorities said the bodies would be handed over to families after further confirmation. Major Kazi Ashraf Hossain was identified by sister Ashrafunnisa, who told reporters she made the primary identification by a scar on the nose. Subedar major Nurul Islam was identified by his son Ashraful Islam, by his beard. 6 officers missing The army had announced the previous day that just six officers were missing, in the wake of the BDR mutiny, revising the figure down from 72 as earlier estimated by military intelligence. There is no official estimate of other missing persons. Ten bodies were among the last discovered in a shallow grave on Feb 28 following the mutiny. The body of the BDR chief's wife was among the ten. Three of those ten bodies remained unidentified at DMCH morgue Wednesday. bdn
